Yep that's correct! You could try the following design: have a state variable `wasInitialized` that starts at false (that's the default, even if you don't do anything in init()), and set it to `true` inside your initialization method. Also, have your initialization method check that it is currently `false`:
```ts
this.wasInitialized.assertEquals(Bool(false));
this.wasInitialized.set(Bool(true));
```

For example:

```typescript
export class SomeContract extends SmartContract {
    @state(Field) commitment = State<Field>();

    @method async init() {
      super.init();
      this.commitment.set(Field(0));
    }

    @method async initialize(commitment: Field) {
        const currentState = this.commitment.get();

        // ensure commitment is not yet set
        currentState.equals(Field(0));

        // set the commitment
        this.commitment.set(commitment);
    }
}
```


then we do


```typescript
  async function localDeploy(commitment: Field) {
    const txn = await Mina.transaction(deployerAccount, async () => {
      AccountUpdate.fundNewAccount(deployerAccount);
      await zkApp.deploy();
      await zkApp.initialize(commitment);
    });
    await txn.prove();
    await txn.sign([deployerKey, zkAppPrivateKey]).send();
  }
```

this will fail with something like

```
    commitment.get() failed, either:
    1. We can't find this zkapp account in the ledger
    2. Because the zkapp account was not found in the cache. Try calling `await fetchAccount(zkappAddress)` first.
    If none of these are the case, then please reach out on Discord at #zkapp-developers and/or open an issue to tell us!

    getAccount: Could not find account for public key B62qmhkQ9o4o6p66EEqn2egtszB81UggdctYY6difiiWsZT5ERdEEoP
```

as `initialize` method needs the account of the contract to exist, so it cannot be run during the deployment

```ts
this.commitment.requireEquals(Field(0));
```

If you want to initialize account's state in the same transaction with the deployment, you don't need to do it with multiple account updates (method calls). The deploy function creates an account update changing the verification key and you can set the state in that same account update.

In your case it would look like this:
```typescript
const txn = await Mina.transaction(deployerAccount, async () => {
  AccountUpdate.fundNewAccount(deployerAccount);
  await zkApp.deploy();
});

txn.transaction.accountUpdates.find(
      (accountUpdate) => accountUpdate.label === 'SomeContract.deploy()'
    )!.update.appState[0] = {
  isSome: Bool(true),
  value: commitment,
};
```

I see that this is not exposed in any convenient way in o1js (I don't see a way to give arguments to the `deploy` and it doesn't return the deployment account update), so I wonder if that's an anti-pattern for some reason @gregor.
